Summary

Data set

The gene expression analysis will be performed on the normalized dataset generated in the previous assignment (#1). Aforementioned data set was procured from the Gene Expression Omnibus (GEO) with GSE196549. The dataset contains a variety of categories to stratify upon and categorize for testing. The variables used in the previous assignment and the variables we will continue to use in this assignment are the phenotype categories which designates if the patient sample is from a patient who has undergone antiretroviral therapy (ART), is an elite controller with no signs of viremia (EC), or a viremic controller with very low signs of viremia (VC). More specifically, there were \(6\) patient samples, \(18\) and \(24\) respectively.

Data set Pre-processing

The dataset was pre-processed via filtering out genes based on patient sample counts where the sum of counts per million (CPM) over patient samples must have been greater than \(30\).

Duplicate rows with exact same values were simply and trivially deleted from the dataset. This reduced the number of genes (rows) by \(14\).

The same dataset was than normalized via trimmed mean of m-values (TMM). TMM was used as we expect that most genes would not be differentially expressed. Furthermore, with TMM, we hoped to reduce technical variation as the process of recording gene expression is very complex with many steps that may introduce such variation.

Preliminary Analysis

The resulting data was pre-emptively analysed at this stage via multidimensional scaling plots (MDS). The produced plot generated 3 groupings where one group was entirely VCs, another was primarily EC and VC, and the last was a mixture of EC, and ART patients.

A dispersion analysis via biological coefficient of variation (BCV) indicated that the produced pre-processed dataset shows that as gene expression increases, the biological coefficient of variation decreases approximately after \(3\log CPM\). This result was validated by plotting the mean variance and seeing that the data largely follows the negative binomial distribution.

phenotype_dge_mds_by <- function(classification_var, title, dge) {
  class_factors <- factor(classification_var)
  col <- c(rainbow(length(unique(classification_var))))
  class_col <- col[class_factors]

  limma::plotMDS(dge, labels = NULL, pch = 1, col = class_col)

  legend("topright", legend = levels(class_factors),
         pch = c(1), col = col, title = title,
         bty = "n", cex = 0.75)

}

We will let \(\alpha = 0.05\). Thus, the following demonstrates the number of samples with p-values below 0.05. The \(\alpha = 0.05\) was selected as that means there is a very little probability (\(5\%\)) chance that the association we see is completely randomly generated, i.e., false positive.

The built in false discovery rate (FDR) multiple testing correction of glmQLFTest was chosen as it offers less false negatives compared to Bonferonni Corrections.

  1. Show the amount of differentially expressed genes using an MA Plot or a Volcano plot. Highlight genes of interest.

We will generate a volcano plot to visualize and further discuss our results.

# Create a basic volcano plot

signif_expr <- 0.25

qlf_art_vs_ec_results$regulation <- apply(
  qlf_art_vs_ec_results[c("FDR", "logFC")],
  MARGIN = 1,
  FUN = function(v) {
    if (v["FDR"] < alpha) {
      if (v["logFC"] >= signif_expr) {
        return("Upregulated")
      } else if (v["logFC"] <= -signif_expr) {
        return("Downregulated")
      }
    }
    return("Insignificant Change")
})

ggplot(
       qlf_art_vs_ec_results,
       aes(x = logFC, y = logFDR, color = regulation)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.4) +
  scale_color_manual(
                     values = c("blue", "grey", "red")) +
  theme_bw() +
  xlab("Log2 Fold Change") +
  ylab("-Log10 Adjusted P-Value") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(-signif_expr, signif_expr), linetype = "dotted") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = -log2(alpha), linetype = "dotted") +
  ggtitle("Expression and Association Levels of Genes")

The top right indicate the upregulated genes and the top left indicate the downregulated genes. We see that there are many genes that were not significant after FDR P-value adjustments.

The above heatmap demonstrates how the different genes perform in association with different HIV outcomes. Immediately, the figure depicts very obvious clustering of genetic expression level changes in the column of patient \(310817\) and antiretroviral therapy patients patients (ARTs). Specifically, we can see very significant clustering of upregulation occurring in genes placed in the upper half of the square, while genes in the lower have are very significantly downregulated. Generally speaking however, there is significant downregulation in the same set of genes that was previously described as upregulated in viremic controller patients (VCs). Elite controllers (ECs) seem to also have a tad more downregulated genes in the upper half set of genes however, still closer to the previously mentioned \(310817\) ART than the general VC set of patients and genes. This corroborates the results seen by the MDS plots where we have some intersections between the different phenotypes.

The next steps involve running g:Profiler programmatically via R. We will try to cache the results when possible with use of the data.table library (Barrett et al. 2024).

query_gprofiler <- function(
    genes,
    cache_name = "") {

  cache_path <- file.path(working_dir, "results", cache_name)
  if (!dir.exists(dirname(cache_path)) && cache_name != "") {
    dir.create(dirname(cache_path))
  }
  if (file.exists(cache_path) && cache_name != "") {
    enrichment_results <- fread(cache_path)
  } else {
gp_results <- gost(query = unlist(genes),
                       significant = FALSE,
                       ordered_query = FALSE,
                       exclude_iea = TRUE,
                       evcodes = TRUE,
                       correction_method = "fdr",
                       organism = organism,
                       domain_scope = "annotated",
                       source = sources)
    enrichment_results <- gp_results$result
    if (cache_name != "") {
      fwrite(enrichment_results, file = cache_path)
    }
  }

  return(enrichment_results)
}

upregulated_enrichment <- query_gprofiler(
  upregulated_genes, 
  "upregulation_results.csv")

downregulated_enrichment <- query_gprofiler(
  downregulated_genes, 
  "downregulation_results.csv")

all_enrichment <- query_gprofiler(
  c(upregulated_genes, downregulated_genes), 
  "all_results.csv")

  1. Run the analysis using the up-regulated set of genes, and the down-regulated set of genes separately. How do these results compare to using the whole list (i.e all differentially expressed genes together vs.the up-regulated and down regulated differentially expressed genes separately)?

In the union set of both up and down regulated genes, we see that there are many more results. This is due to there being more potential genes to partake in various pathways than any individual. Furthermore, for the same reason, there are many more results where the range of possible intersection sizes is increased and the relative number of larger term sizes may also be increased.

Interpretation

The assignment outline requires the following.

  1. Do the over-representation results support conclusions or mechanism discussed in the original paper?

Yes, the over-representation results support the general conclusions discussed in the original paper. To elaborate, the paper specifically discusses the increase of CD8+ T cells within germinal centers (Collins et al. 2023). This corresponds with the several up-regulation of positive regulation pathways of T-cells. This ranges from T-cell differentiation pathways to T-cell activation pathways.

  1. Can you find evidence, i.e.publications, to support some of the results that you see. How does this evidence support your results.

Diving into the specifics, we can see there is an upregulation of various immune cell differentiation. This corroborates the general theory that the virus has some capacity to surpress the operations of the immune system (Deng et al. 2018).

In terms of down-regulation, several pathways associated with the lifecycle of a cell have very large intersections and highly significant p-values. This is also a known effect of HIV-1 and has been previously studied (Piekna-Przybylska and Maggirwar 2018). Furthermore, the results obtained seem to indicate various regulations in mRNA machinery are downregulated. This is also a well known effect with various papers citing as such (Toro-Ascuy et al. 2016; Wang et al. 2022).
